# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alkali
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] Abhik Ghosh was born in Kolkata, West Bengal, India, in 1964.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] As a child, he learned Sanskrit from his grandmother Ila Ghosh (née Roy), a language he still speaks and reads fluently.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] (Honours) in chemistry from Jadavpur University, Kolkata, India, in 1987, winning the University Medal of the Faculty of Science.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] The same year, he moved to the University of Minnesota, where he completed a PhD under the supervision of Regents' Professor Paul G.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] Gassman (while also collaborating with Jan Almlöf) in 1992 and subsequently also postdoctoral research with Lawrence Que Jr.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] During this period, Abhik reported some of the first high-quality ab initio and density functional theory calculations on bioinorganic systems, helping lay the foundation of the now thriving field of computational bioinorganic chemistry.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] He did a brief, second postdoc with David Bocian at the University of California Riverside, in the course of which he derived significant new insight into the problem diatomic ligand discrimination by heme proteins.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] After postdoctoral stints in Minnesota and California, Abhik moved to UiT – The Arctic University of Norway in 1996, where he has remained ever since.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] He has authored/coauthored over 300 scientific papers, which have been cited over 13,000 times with an h-index of 65 (according to Google Scholar).
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] He has received many awards for teaching and research, including the Olav Thon Prize for Outstanding Teaching (2025) and the Hans Fischer Career Award for Lifetime Contributions to Porphyrin Chemistry.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] He is a member of several national and international academies including the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters, the Norwegian Academy of Technological Sciences, the Academia Borealis, the European Academy of Sciences, and the Academia Europaea.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] He edited two books, *The Smallest Biomolecules: Diatomics and their Interactions with Heme Proteins* (Elsevier, 2008), a monograph on the subject, and *Letters to a Young Chemist* (Wiley, 2011), a popular science book on careers in chemistry research.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] In 2014, he coauthored *Arrow Pushing in Inorganic Chemistry: A Logical Approach to the Chemistry of the Main Group Elements* (Wiley) with Steffen Berg, which won the 2015 Prose Award for 'best textbook in the Physical Sciences and Mathematics'.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] Ghosh has contributed to many areas of porphyrin-related research.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] Ghosh has also published popular articles on arrow pushing, on the occasion of the 100th anniversary of its first use by Sir Robert Robinson, and on the impact of relativity in chemistry, among many others.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] As a queer chemist, Ghosh has been involved in a variety of diversity initiatives.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] The 2011 book *Letters to a Young Chemist* with a young woman as the protagonist and several contributions by leading female scientists has gone through numerous reprints and remains a bestseller.
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] In 2020–2021, Ghosh published two biographical essays on the late Martin Gouterman, a noted porphyrin chemist and one of the first openly gay/LGBT scientists, drawing a parallel with astronomer and gay rights activist Frank Kameny (see LGBT history for a more general discussion).
[src:alkali/abhik-ghosh] Subsequently, he co-edited a Virtual Issue on “Out in Inorganic Chemistry: A Celebration of LGBTQIAPN+ Inorganic Chemists” highlighting queer authors in *Inorganic Chemistry* and other American Chemical Society journals.
[src:alkali/academic-press] Academic Press publishes books and reference materials in fields including communications engineering, economics, environmental science, finance, food science, geophysics, life sciences, mathematics, neuroscience, psychology, and the physical sciences.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] In chemistry, an **acid–base reaction** is a chemical reaction that occurs between an acid and a base.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] It can be used to determine pH via titration.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Several theoretical frameworks provide alternative conceptions of the reaction mechanisms and their application in solving related problems; these are called the acid–base theories, for example, Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Their importance becomes apparent in analyzing acid–base reactions for gaseous or liquid species, or when acid or base character may be somewhat less apparent.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The first of these concepts was provided by the French chemist Antoine Lavoisier, around 1776.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] It is important to think of the acid–base reaction models as theories that complement each other.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] For example, the current Lewis model has the broadest definition of what an acid and base are, with the Brønsted–Lowry theory being a subset of what acids and bases are, and the Arrhenius theory being the most restrictive.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The Arrhenius theory describes an acid as a substance that increases the concentration of hydrogen ions (H3O+ or H+) in a solution.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] A base is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide ions (OH-) in a solution.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] However, Arrhenius's definition only applies to substances that are in water.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The concept of an acid–base reaction was first proposed in 1754 by Guillaume-François Rouelle, who introduced the word "base" into chemistry to mean a substance which reacts with an acid to give it solid form (as a salt).
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The first scientific concept of acids and bases was provided by Lavoisier in around 1776.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The Lavoisier definition held for over 30 years, until the 1810 article and subsequent lectures by Sir Humphry Davy in which he proved the lack of oxygen in hydrogen sulfide (H2S), hydrogen telluride (H2Te), and the hydrohalic acids.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] However, Davy failed to develop a new theory, concluding that "acidity does not depend upon any particular elementary substance, but upon peculiar arrangement of various substances".
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] One notable modification of oxygen theory was provided by Jöns Jacob Berzelius, who stated that acids are oxides of nonmetals while bases are oxides of metals.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] In 1838, Justus von Liebig proposed that an acid is a hydrogen-containing compound whose hydrogen can be replaced by a metal.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] This redefinition was based on his extensive work on the chemical composition of organic acids, finishing the doctrinal shift from oxygen-based acids to hydrogen-based acids started by Davy.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Liebig's definition, while completely empirical, remained in use for almost 50 years until the adoption of the Arrhenius definition.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The first modern definition of acids and bases in molecular terms was devised by Svante Arrhenius.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] A hydrogen theory of acids, it followed from his 1884 work with Friedrich Wilhelm Ostwald in establishing the presence of ions in aqueous solution and led to Arrhenius receiving the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1903.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] This causes the protonation of water, or the creation of the hydronium (H3O+) ion.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Thus, in modern times, the symbol H+ is interpreted as a shorthand for H3O+, because it is now known that a bare proton does not exist as a free species in aqueous solution.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] This is the species which is measured by pH indicators to measure the acidity or basicity of a solution.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The Arrhenius definitions of acidity and alkalinity are restricted to aqueous solutions and are not valid for most non-aqueous solutions, and refer to the concentration of the solvent ions.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Under this definition, pure H2SO4 and HCl dissolved in toluene are not acidic, and molten NaOH and solutions of calcium amide in liquid ammonia are not alkaline.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] This led to the development of the Brønsted–Lowry theory and subsequent Lewis theory to account for these non-aqueous exceptions.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The reaction of an acid with a base is called a neutralization reaction.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] In this traditional representation an acid–base neutralization reaction is formulated as a double-replacement reaction.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The modifier (aq) in this equation was implied by Arrhenius, rather than included explicitly.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] It indicates that the substances are dissolved in water.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Though all three substances, HCl, NaOH and NaCl are capable of existing as pure compounds, in aqueous solutions they are fully dissociated into the aquated ions H+, Cl−, Na+ and OH−.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Baking powder is used to cause the dough for breads and cakes to "rise" by creating millions of tiny carbon dioxide bubbles.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Baking powder is not to be confused with baking soda, which is sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3).
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Baking powder is a mixture of baking soda (sodium bicarbonate) and acidic salts.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The bubbles are created because, when the baking powder is combined with water, the sodium bicarbonate and acid salts react to produce gaseous carbon dioxide.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Whether commercially or domestically prepared, the principles behind baking powder formulations remain the same.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The real reactions are more complicated because the acids are complicated.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] A typical formulation (by weight) could call for 30% sodium bicarbonate, 5–12% monocalcium phosphate, and 21–26% sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Alternately, a commercial baking powder might use sodium acid pyrophosphate as one of the two acidic components instead of sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Another typical acid in such formulations is cream of tartar (KC4H5O6), a derivative of tartaric acid.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] An acid–base reaction is, thus, the removal of a proton from the acid and its addition to the base.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The removal of a proton from an acid produces its *conjugate base*, which is the acid with a proton removed.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The reception of a proton by a base produces its *conjugate acid*, which is the base with a proton added.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Unlike the previous definitions, the Brønsted–Lowry definition does not refer to the formation of salt and solvent, but instead to the formation of *conjugate acids* and *conjugate bases*, produced by the transfer of a proton from the acid to the base.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] In this approach, acids and bases are fundamentally different in behavior from salts, which are seen as electrolytes, subject to the theories of Debye, Onsager, and others.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] An acid and a base react not to produce a salt and a solvent, but to form a new acid and a new base.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The concept of neutralization is thus absent.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base behavior is formally independent of any solvent, making it more all-encompassing than the Arrhenius model.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The calculation of pH under the Arrhenius model depended on alkalis (bases) dissolving in water (aqueous solution).
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The Brønsted–Lowry model expanded what could be pH tested using insoluble and soluble solutions (gas, liquid, solid).
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The general formula for acid–base reactions according to the Brønsted–Lowry definition is: ${\ce {HA + B -> BH+ + A-}}$ where HA represents the acid, B represents the base, BH+ represents the conjugate acid of B, and A− represents the conjugate base of HA.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The removal of H+ from the HCl produces the chloride ion, Cl−, the conjugate base of the acid.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The addition of H+ to the H2O (acting as a base) forms the hydronium ion, H3O+, the conjugate acid of the base.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Water is amphoteric – that is, it can act as both an acid and a base.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Here, one molecule of water acts as an acid, donating an H+ and forming the conjugate base, OH−, and a second molecule of water acts as a base, accepting the H+ ion and forming the conjugate acid, H3O+.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] In this example, a water molecule is split into a hydrogen cation, which is donated to a pyridine molecule, and a hydroxide ion.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] In the Brønsted–Lowry model, the solvent does not necessarily have to be water, as is required by the Arrhenius Acid–Base model.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] An H+ ion is removed from acetic acid, forming its conjugate base, the acetate ion, CH3COO−.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The addition of an H+ ion to an ammonia molecule of the solvent creates its conjugate acid, the ammonium ion, NH+4.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The Brønsted–Lowry model calls hydrogen-containing substances (like HCl) acids.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Thus, some substances, which many chemists considered to be acids, such as SO3 or BCl3, are excluded from this classification due to lack of hydrogen.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The hydrogen requirement of Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry was removed by the Lewis definition of acid–base reactions, devised by Gilbert N.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Lewis in 1923, in the same year as Brønsted–Lowry, but it was not elaborated by him until 1938.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Instead of defining acid–base reactions in terms of protons or other bonded substances, the Lewis definition defines a base (referred to as a *Lewis base*) to be a compound that can donate an *electron pair*, and an acid (a *Lewis acid*) to be a compound that can receive this electron pair.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] For example, boron trifluoride, BF3 is a typical Lewis acid.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] It can accept a pair of electrons as it has a vacancy in its octet.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The fluoride ion has a full octet and can donate a pair of electrons.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Thus ${\ce {BF3 + F- -> BF4-}}$ is a typical Lewis acid, Lewis base reaction.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] All compounds of group 13 elements with a formula AX3 can behave as Lewis acids.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Similarly, compounds of group 15 elements with a formula DY3, such as amines, NR3, and phosphines, PR3, can behave as Lewis bases.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Adducts between them have the formula X3A←DY3 with a dative covalent bond, shown symbolically as ←, between the atoms A (acceptor) and D (donor).
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Compounds of group 16 with a formula DX2 may also act as Lewis bases; in this way, a compound like an ether, R2O, or a thioether, R2S, can act as a Lewis base.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The Lewis definition is not limited to these examples.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] For instance, carbon monoxide acts as a Lewis base when it forms an adduct with boron trifluoride, of formula F3B←CO.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Adducts involving metal ions are referred to as co-ordination compounds; each ligand donates a pair of electrons to the metal ion.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The reaction ${\ce {[Ag(H2O)4]+ + 2 NH3 -> [Ag(NH3)2]+ + 4 H2O}}$ can be seen as an acid–base reaction in which a stronger base (ammonia) replaces a weaker one (water).
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The Lewis and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are consistent with each other since the reaction ${\ce {H+ + OH- <=> H2O}}$ is an acid–base reaction in both theories.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] One of the limitations of the Arrhenius definition is its reliance on water solutions.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Edward Curtis Franklin studied the acid–base reactions in liquid ammonia in 1905 and pointed out the similarities to the water-based Arrhenius theory.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Germann, working with liquid phosgene, COCl 2, formulated the solvent-based theory in 1925, thereby generalizing the Arrhenius definition to cover aprotic solvents.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvonium ions and a decrease in the concentration of solvate ions is defined as an *acid*.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvate ions and a decrease in the concentration of the solvonium ions is defined as a *base*.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Thus, in liquid ammonia, KNH2 (supplying NH−2) is a strong base, and NH4NO3 (supplying NH+4) is a strong acid.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] In liquid sulfur dioxide (SO2), thionyl compounds (supplying SO2+) behave as acids, and sulfites (supplying SO2−3) behave as bases.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] On the other hand, solvent system theory has been criticized as being too general to be useful.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Also, it has been thought that there is something intrinsically acidic about hydrogen compounds, a property not shared by non-hydrogenic solvonium salts.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] This acid–base theory was a revival of the oxygen theory of acids and bases proposed by German chemist Hermann Lux in 1939, further improved by Håkon Flood c.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] 1947 and is still used in modern geochemistry and electrochemistry of molten salts.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] This definition describes an acid as an oxide ion (O2−) acceptor and a base as an oxide ion donor.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] This theory is also useful in the systematisation of the reactions of noble gas compounds, especially the xenon oxides, fluorides, and oxofluorides.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Mikhail Usanovich developed a general theory that does not restrict acidity to hydrogen-containing compounds, but his approach, published in 1938, was even more general than Lewis theory.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Usanovich's theory can be summarized as defining an acid as anything that accepts negative species or donates positive ones, and a base as the reverse.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] This defined the concept of redox (oxidation-reduction) as a special case of acid–base reactions.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] In 1963, Ralph Pearson proposed a qualitative concept known as the Hard and Soft Acids and Bases principle. later made quantitative with help of Robert Parr in 1984.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] 'Hard' applies to species that are small, have high charge states, and are weakly polarizable.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] 'Soft' applies to species that are large, have low charge states and are strongly polarizable.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Acids and bases interact, and the most stable interactions are hard–hard and soft–soft.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] This theory has found use in organic and inorganic chemistry.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Drago is a quantitative model that describes and predicts the strength of Lewis acid base interactions, −Δ*H*.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The model assigned E and C parameters to many Lewis acids and bases.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Each acid is characterized by an *E*A and a *C*A.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Each base is likewise characterized by its own *E*B and *C*B.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The E and C parameters refer, respectively, to the electrostatic and covalent contributions to the strength of the bonds that the acid and base will form.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The W term represents a constant energy contribution for acid–base reaction such as the cleavage of a dimeric acid or base.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The equation predicts reversal of acids and base strengths.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The graphical presentations of the equation show that there is no single order of Lewis base strengths or Lewis acid strengths.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The reaction of a strong acid with a strong base is essentially a quantitative reaction.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] In this reaction both the sodium and chloride ions are spectators as the neutralization reaction, ${\ce {H+ + OH- -> H2O}}$ does not involve them.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] With weak bases addition of acid is not quantitative because a solution of a weak base is a buffer solution.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] A solution of a weak acid is also a buffer solution.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] When a weak acid reacts with a weak base an equilibrium mixture is produced.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] The notation [X] signifies "concentration of X".
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] An acid–alkali reaction is a special case of an acid–base reaction, where the base used is also an alkali.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] When an acid reacts with an alkali salt (a metal hydroxide), the product is a metal salt and water.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Acid–alkali reactions are also neutralization reactions.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Acids are in general pure substances that contain hydrogen cations (H+) or cause them to be produced in solutions.
[src:alkali/acid-base-reaction-theories] Hydrochloric acid (HCl) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4) are common examples.
[src:alkali/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:alkali/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:alkali/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:alkali/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:alkali/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:alkali/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:alkali/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:alkali/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:alkali/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:alkali/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:alkali/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:alkali/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:alkali/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:alkali/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:alkali/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:alkali/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:alkali/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:alkali/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:alkali/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:alkali/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:alkali/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:alkali/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:alkali/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:alkali/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:alkali/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:alkali/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:alkali/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:alkali/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:alkali/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:alkali/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:alkali/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:alkali/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:alkali/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:alkali/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:alkali/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:alkali/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:alkali/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:alkali/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:alkali/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:alkali/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:alkali/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:alkali/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:alkali/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:alkali/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:alkali/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:alkali/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:alkali/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:alkali/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:alkali/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:alkali/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:alkali/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:alkali/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:alkali/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:alkali/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:alkali/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:alkali/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:alkali/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:alkali/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:alkali/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:alkali/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:alkali/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:alkali/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:alkali/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:alkali/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:alkali/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:alkali/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:alkali/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:alkali/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:alkali/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:alkali/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:alkali/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:alkali/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:alkali/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:alkali/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:alkali/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:alkali/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:alkali/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:alkali/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:alkali/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:alkali/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:alkali/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:alkali/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:alkali/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:alkali/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:alkali/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:alkali/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:alkali/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:alkali/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:alkali/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:alkali/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:alkali/alkali-lake-oregon] Alkali Lake is believed to have reached a prehistoric maximum depth of 270.7 feet (82.5 meters) and covered about 1,448.4 square miles (3,751 square kilometers).
[src:alkali/alkali-lake-oregon] Since then, its water level has fluctuated, with a general trend towards drying.
[src:alkali/alkali-lake-oregon] Notable features include dissolved alkaline salts averaging 10% of total brine weight in its seasonal waters and a nearby chemical disaster, Alkali Lake Chemical Waste Dump.
[src:alkali/alkali-lake-oregon] According to the Köppen Climate Classification system, Alkali Lake has a steppe climate, abbreviated "BSk" on climate maps.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] Historically, sodium hydroxide was produced by treating sodium carbonate (usually from seaweed ash or "glasswort"-plant ash) with calcium hydroxide (a.k.a. lime) in a metathesis reaction.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] (Sodium hydroxide is soluble while calcium carbonate is not.) This process was called causticizing.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] The Leblanc process, which was invented by Nicolas Leblanc around 1790, begins with the decomposition of sodium chloride by sulfuric acid, by which sodium sulfate and hydrochloric acid are produced.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] The sodium sulfate is afterwards fired with calcium carbonate and coal.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] Sodium carbonate can be extracted from this mixture by washing the mixture with water.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] Until the rise of the ammonia-soda process, which has better economics, the Leblanc process was used extensively making the United Kingdom the lead in alkali production.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] By the early 20th century, the UK's production outstripped that of all other producers combined.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] Most of the British alkali works are situated in South Lancashire and the adjoining part of Cheshire, near the mouth of the Tyne and in the West of Scotland.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] In the 1870s the lime process was revolutionary improved to result in the ammonia-soda process, which is the most common method today.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] However, its actual implementation of this overall reaction is very inventive.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] A simplified description can be given using the four different, interacting chemical reactions illustrated in the figure.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] In the first step in the process, carbon dioxide (CO2) passes through a concentrated aqueous solution of sodium chloride (table salt, NaCl) and ammonia (NH3).
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] In industrial practice, the reaction is carried out by passing concentrated brine (salt water) through two towers.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] In the first, ammonia bubbles up through the brine and is absorbed by it.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] In the second, carbon dioxide bubbles up through the ammoniated brine, and sodium bicarbonate (baking soda) precipitates out of the solution.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] Note that, in a basic solution, NaHCO3 is less water-soluble than sodium chloride.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] The ammonia (NH3) buffers the solution at a basic (high) pH; without the ammonia, a hydrochloric acid byproduct would render the solution acidic, and arrest the precipitation.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] Here, NH3 along with ammoniacal brine acts as a mother liquor.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] The only way in which the Leblanc process could still hold its own was by being turned in the direction of making caustic soda, to which it lends itself more easily than the ammonia-soda process; but the latter has invaded even this field.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] One advantage, however, still remained to the Leblanc process.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] All endeavours to obtain either hydrochloric acid or free chlorine in the ammonia-soda process have proved commercial failures, all the chlorine of the sodium chloride being ultimately lost in the shape of worthless calcium chloride.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] The Leblanc process thus remained the sole purveyor of chlorine in its active forms, and in this way the fact is accounted for that, at least in Great Britain, the Leblanc process still furnishes nearly half of all the alkali made, though in other countries its proportional share is much less.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] The profit made upon the chlorine produced has to make up for the loss on the alkali.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] The ammonia-soda process was first patented on 30 June 1838 by Harrison Gray Dyar and John Hemming, who carried it out on an experimental scale in Whitechapel.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] Many attempts were soon after made in the same direction, both in England and on the continent of Europe, the most remarkable of which was the ingenious combination of apparatus devised by J.
[src:alkali/alkali-manufacture] But a really economical solution of the problem was first definitely found in 1872 by Ernest Solvay, as the result of investigations begun about ten years previously.
[src:alkali/alkali] In chemistry, an **alkali** (/ˈælkəlaɪ/ ⓘ; from the Arabic word *al-qaly*, القالِي "saltwort") also **base** is a hydroxide of any of either the alkali metal which are Group I s-block elements, or the alkaline earth metal which are Group II s-block.
[src:alkali/alkali] *Alkali* can also be defined as a base that dissolves in water.
[src:alkali/alkali] A solution of a soluble base has a pH greater than 7.0.
[src:alkali/alkali] The adjectives ***alkaline*** and, less often, ***alkalescent*** are commonly used in English as a synonyms for *basic*, especially for bases soluble in water.
[src:alkali/alkali] This broad use of the term is likely to have come about because alkalis were the first bases known to obey the Arrhenius definition of a base, and they are still among the most common bases.
[src:alkali/alkali] The word *alkali* is derived from Arabic *al qalīy* (or *alkali*), meaning 'the calcined ashes' (see calcination), referring to the original source of alkaline substances.
[src:alkali/alkali] A water-extract of burned plant ashes, called *potash* and composed mostly of potassium carbonate, was mildly basic.
[src:alkali/alkali] After heating this substance with calcium hydroxide (*slaked lime*), a far more strongly basic substance known as *caustic potash* (potassium hydroxide) was produced.
[src:alkali/alkali] Caustic potash was traditionally used in conjunction with animal fats to produce soft soaps, one of the caustic processes that rendered soaps from fats in the process of saponification, one known since antiquity.
[src:alkali/alkali] Plant potash lent the name to the element potassium, which was first derived from caustic potash, and also gave potassium its chemical symbol **K** (from the German name *Kalium*), which ultimately derived from al**k**ali.
[src:alkali/alkali] Alkalis are all Arrhenius bases, ones which form hydroxide ions (OH−) when dissolved in water.
[src:alkali/alkali] The terms "base" and "alkali" are often used interchangeably, particularly outside the context of chemistry and chemical engineering.
[src:alkali/alkali] There are various, more specific definitions for the concept of an alkali.
[src:alkali/alkali] Alkalis are usually defined as a subset of the bases.
[src:alkali/alkali] The second subset of bases is also called an "Arrhenius base".
[src:alkali/alkali] Soils with pH values that are higher than 7.3 are usually defined as being alkaline.
[src:alkali/alkali] These soils can occur naturally due to the presence of alkali salts.
[src:alkali/alkali] Although many plants do prefer slightly basic soil (including vegetables like cabbage and fodder like buffalo grass), most plants prefer mildly acidic soil (with pHs between 6.0 and 6.8), and alkaline soils can cause problems.
[src:alkali/alkali] In alkali lakes (also called *soda lakes*), evaporation concentrates the naturally occurring carbonate salts, giving rise to an alkalic and often saline lake.
